solutions.content:
#### Explanations
Greedy problem tends to be harder I feel, but here is a crucial observation that we need. 
For any element that is free to either start a new subsequence or appending to an existing subsequence,
it is always preferable to append, instead of starting anew.
The reason is that, there is no situation in which starting anew will be benefited. In fact, starting anew requires us to add at least 2 elements after it, but there is no such restriction if we just append it to existing valid subsequences.

#### Implementation
With this insight, we can code it up with 2 arrays style. 
`count[i]: The count of available number i that can be used.`
`end[i]: The number of valid subsequences that end with number i`.
Then, for each number `i`, we check how many `end[i-1]` we can take `= min(end[i-1], count[i])`, and the remaining will have to be the head of new subsequences.

`Time O(N)`
`Space O(2003)`
####  Java
```Java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPossible(int[] nums) {
        int[] count = new int[2003];
        int[] end = new int[2003];
        for (int n : nums){
            count[n+1000]++;
        }
        for (int i = 0; i <= 2002; i++){
            if (count[i] < 0){ // can't be less than 0, return false
                return false;
            }else if (i <= 2000){
                int cont = Math.min(count[i], i==0?0:end[i-1]); // extend the subsequences
                count[i] -= cont;
                end[i] += cont;
                count[i+1] -= count[i]; // start some new subsequences and we must take those
                count[i+2] -= count[i]; // take those 
                end[i+2] += count[i];   // update end to include the new subsequences.
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

