solutions.content:
**Intuition**

We can solve this problem with yet another greedy strategy.

Compared to the other greedy algorithm posted by me, this algorithm is clearer via looking ahead.
**Implementation**

We use two hash maps. cntcntcnt for the remaining frequency of each number, while subssubssubs for the number of subsequences that end with a certain number.

Since the original array is sorted, we just process the numbers sequentially. For each number:

*     First, if the frequency of numnumnum is already zero, this means numnumnum has been used by previous numbers, so we just skip it.
*     Then, we consider adding it to an existing subsequence. We can check sub[num−1]sub[num-1]sub[num−1] for that.
*     Next, we try to make a new subsequence with num,num+1,num+2num,num+1,num+2num,num+1,num+2. (This is looking ahead.)
*     Otherwise, we cannot put numnumnum into any suitable subsequence, so the test case has no valid answer.

**Time Complexity**

Time complexity is O(n)\mathcal{O}(n)O(n) for the loop through all numbers.
**Space Complexity**

Space complexity is O(n)\mathcal{O}(n)O(n) for the hash map.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int, int> freq, end;
        for(auto i:nums)freq[i]++;
        for(auto i:nums){
            if( freq[i] <= 0)continue;
            if(end[i-1] > 0){
                end[i-1]--;
                freq[i]--;
                end[i]++;
            }
            else if( freq[i+1] and  freq[i+2] ){
                freq[i]--;
                freq[i+1]--;
                freq[i+2]--;
                end[i+2]++;
            }
            else return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

