Approach:
The maximum frequency of an element that can be accomodated is the number of subsequences that can start at it + number of subsequences that end at it + number of subsequences in which number can come in between.

Number of subsequences that can start from element i : start = min(freq[i+1],freq[i+2]);
Number of subsequences that can end at element i : end = min(freq[i-1],freq[i-2]);
Number of subsequences in which i can come in between : mid = min(freq[i+1]-start,freq[i-1]-end);

if the freq[i] is more than start+end+mid then we can not form the required subsequence and false is returned, otherwise true is returned


Since frequency of each element is stored in a map,
Space Complexity : O(n)

Since each element of array will be traversed twice(once for freq calculation and once for checking),
Time Complexity : O(n) 

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int,int> freq;
        for(int i : nums){
            freq[i]++;
        }

        for(auto& i:nums){
            int ft = freq[i];
            int end = min(freq[i-1],freq[i-2]); //max no of sub sequences ending at i
            int start = min(freq[i+1],freq[i+2]); //max no of subsequences starting at i 
            ft = ft - end - start - min(freq[i+1]-start,freq[i-1]-end); 
            if(ft>0){
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

