solutions.content:
The idea is we go through the `nums`  and try to construct a sequence in a greedy manner:

Assume the first number we get is `n`, and it appears `k` times, then, if the next number is `n + 1` and it appears at least `k` times, 
we can be sure that we need to include `n + 1` into our current sequence.

If the next number is not `n + 1`, we have to conclude the current sequence.

If the next number appears less than `k` times, we also have to conclude the current sequence, because `n + 1` needs to be included in another sequence containing `n`.

After we get a sequence, we check if it has length ` >= 3 `. If not, we know it is not possible to split the array into consecutive subsequences, and we return `false`.

We return `true` if `nums` is empty and the last sequence we constructed has length ` >= 3 `.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int, int> hm;
        for(auto num : nums) {
            hm[num] ++;
        } 
        while(1) {
            int prevVal = -1, currVal = -1;
            int cnt = 0;
            bool start = true;
            for(auto it = nums.begin(); it != nums.end();) {
                if(start) {
                    currVal = *it;
                    it = nums.erase(it);
                    hm[currVal] --;
                    cnt ++;
                    start = false;
                } else if(*it == currVal) { // If we meet a duplicate, move forward.
                    it ++;
                } else {
                    prevVal = currVal;
                    currVal = *it;
                    // If 
                    // 1. count of current value is >= count of previous value (we need +1  because when we take previous value, its count is decreased).
                    // 2. currVal is consecutive of previous value.
                    // we increase count.
                    if(hm[currVal] >= hm[prevVal] + 1 && currVal == prevVal + 1) { 
                        it = nums.erase(it);
                        hm[currVal] --;
                        cnt ++;
                    } else {
                        // If current sequence we constructed has size < 3, we return false.
                        if(cnt < 3) {
                            return false;
                        } else {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
            // If we have processed all the numbers, we have to check the count of the last sequence we constructed.
            if(nums.empty()) {
                if(cnt >= 3) {
                    return true;
                }
                return false;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
```

