solutions.content:
The idea is that if the current element of the array has more duplicates than the previous one, then we need new subsequences starting from these increased duplicates; if the current element has less duplicates or the consecutive number is missing, then some (or all for missing numbers) subsequences stored previously should be cut since there are not enough duplicates to continue them all.

The subsequences begin earlier should end earlier to make more subsquences to get enough size (>= 3). We may store the starting elements of the subsequences in a queue. When the number of duplicates decreases, the staring elements of previous subsequences pop out and we may check the validity of them by comparing the starting elements and the element where they end; when more duplicates show up, we may offer new starting elements to the queue for the newly appeared subsequences.

For example, for input array [1,2,3,3,4,5], the number of duplicates increases at element 1, since it's the very first element. We offer 1 to the queue. The number of duplicates increases again at 3, bigger than the size of the queue which represents how many alive subseqences so far, so we offer 3 to the queue and start a new subsequence. At element 4, the number of duplicates decreases by 1, which means we need cut 1 previous subsequence. The earliest subsequence starts from element 1, we check its validity by calculating its size 4 - 1 = 3. Finally, after visiting the last element 5, we need check the validity of the remaining subsequence starting from 3. It is valid and the result is true.

```
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPossible(int[] nums) {
        Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        int prev = 0; // the previous distinct element in array "nums"
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int count = 1;
            while (i + 1 < nums.length && nums[i] == nums[i + 1]) { // count repetitions
                i++;
                count++;
            }
            if (i > 0 && nums[i] > prev + 1) { // if it is not consecutive, then check all previous subsequences
                if (!valid(queue, prev, 0))
                    return false;
            }
            int size = queue.size();
            if (count > size) { // if the array "expands", new subsequences appear
                for (int j = 0; j < count - size; j++)
                    queue.offer(nums[i]);
            }
            else if (count < size) { // if the array "shrinks", some old subsequences end
                if (!valid(queue, prev, count))
                    return false;
            }
            prev = nums[i];
        }
        if (!valid(queue, nums[nums.length - 1], 0)) // if there are subsequences left that have not been checked
            return false;
        return true;
    }
    public boolean valid(Queue<Integer> queue, int lastEle, int count) { // check subsequences stored previously, "lastEle" stands for the last element of the completed subsequences, "count" denotes the number of subsquences "alive" which need not a check now
        int size = queue.size();
        for (int j = 0; j < size - count; j++) {
            int start = queue.poll();
            if (lastEle - start + 1 < 3)
                return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
````

