solutions.content:
Similar to 846. Hand of Straights, but instead used an unordered_map to count since the original array is sorted.
For each number n, we increment it to get a `Consecutive Subsequences`. But when to stop?
1. If `count[n+1] > count[n]`, which means that there are more `n+1` than `n`, then we can add `n+1` to the array. It is because there is extra `n+1` and it makes no difference whether you put it with the current subsequences or a latter one (but there might not be latter valid subsequence).
2. Otherwise we stop here. An example might be `[1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4]`, when `n == 3`, you would be better off stopping here instead of taking 4 because `(count[4] == 1) <= (2 == count[3])`
```c++
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int, int> cnt;
        for (int i: nums) cnt[i] += 1;

        int prev_cnt = 0, hi = 0;
        for (int lo: nums){
            if (!cnt[lo]) continue;
            prev_cnt = cnt[lo]--, hi=lo;
            while(++hi){
                if (cnt[hi] >= prev_cnt) prev_cnt = cnt[hi]--;
                else break;
            }
            if (hi - lo < 3) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

