[Updated on 05/17/2020] I just realized that we don't need a <Integer, PriorityQueue> map. Instead, we just need two PriorityQueue to store the previous sequence ended at nums[i]-1 and current sequece ended at nums[i]. New code is attached below. 

The basic idea is to look for a previous sequence to attach current element onto it. If there are multiple previous sequences, select the one with smallest length (hence we need the PriorityQueue).

If no applicable previous sequence exists, build a new sequence.

```
class Solution {
    //use two PriorityQueue: one for sequence ended at num-1
    //the other for sequence ended at num
    public boolean isPossible(int[] nums) {
        int n=nums.length;
        if(n<3) return false;

        PriorityQueue<Integer> prev=new PriorityQueue<Integer>();
        PriorityQueue<Integer> curr=new PriorityQueue<Integer>();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(prev.isEmpty()){
                curr.add(1);
            }
            else{
                curr.add(prev.poll()+1);
            }

            //prev sequence will not continue
            //need to check length
            if(i==n-1|| nums[i+1]!=nums[i]){
                if(!prev.isEmpty() && prev.peek()<3){
                    return false;
                } 
                //clear since it will not continue
                prev.clear();
            }

            if(i==n-1 || nums[i+1]>nums[i]+1){
                //current sequence will not continue
                if(curr.peek()<3){
                    return false;
                } 
                curr.clear();
            }
            else{
                //curr sequence will continue
                //need to become prev sequence if next element is different
                if(i<n-1 && nums[i+1]!=nums[i]){
                    while(!curr.isEmpty()){
                        prev.add(curr.poll());
                    } 
                }       
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
