solutions.content:
```
/*  While iterating through the array, each element has 2 choices. Either get appended to existing subsequence or create its own subsequence.
    1) Append to existing subsequence: To get appended, we check if element i exists in HM with its value greater than 0. If true, we append to it. 
    To append, we simply decrement HM[i] and its count in freq[i]. Next, create a spot for i+1 element that can be appended if it exists in array.

    2) Create own subsequence: To create a new subsequence with element i, then you need to have minimum of 3 elements that are consecutive, i.e., i, i+1 and i+2.
    If minimum of 3 subsequence exists, then decrement their corresponding freq[i] and create a spot in HM[i+3], where i+3 element can be appended to this list in future, if it exists in the array.

    3) If neither of above two conditions satisfy, then you cannot form a subsequence with minimum of 3 consecutive elements. Return false

    If 1) and 2) conditions passes, then return true at the end.

    Credit to this approach: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJ8BAQ8lASE
*/

    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {

        map<int, int> freq, HM; //HM means Hypothetical Map

        //Calculate freq of numbers
        for(int i : nums) freq[i]++;

        for(int i : nums)
        {
            if(freq[i] == 0) continue; //If count of element i is 0, then it is already used up in subsequence. Continue to next element.
            else if(HM[i] > 0)
            {
                HM[i]--;
                HM[i+1]++;
                freq[i]--;
            }
            //create a new subsequence
            else if(freq[i] > 0 && freq[i+1] > 0 && freq[i+2] > 0)
            {
                freq[i]--;
                freq[i+1]--;
                freq[i+2]--;

                HM[i+3]++;
            }
            else return false;
        }
        return true;

    }
