solutions.content:
**Approach**
* Initialise a multiset of pairs where (p, q)  = (last_element, length)
* Let current element be x. Pick a pair from multiset such that p = x - 1 (so that you can add x to this sequence) and q => minimum length corresponding to such p. We can find it using **lower_bound** in multiset.
* Once found, erase that pair (x - 1, q) & insert (x, q + 1) since last element is now x & length of this sequence increases by 1.
* After all operations, iterate over the queue if not empty. If there exists a q < 3, then return false since there exists a sequence of length < 3. If no, return true.

**Questions**
Why mutliset?
* We need a data structure such that it is sorted by the last element of the sequence as well as the length of the sequence it belongs to. So lets create a pair<last_element, length>. Since we need it to be sorted by both, lets use multiset.
* How does this work?
	* Suppose my current element is x. I need to add this x in a sequence whose last element is x - 1. How do I find that sequence? And, if there are multiple such sequences, where do I insert the x? Simple - since we are using multiset, searching would be done in O(logn) using lower_bound. And in case of multiple such sequences, always choose one with the minimum length - since we need the size to be atleast 3. That's why, we need to sort by length too so that in case of multiple (x - 1)s, we add x in the sequence of minimum length.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(vector<int>& nums) {
        multiset<pair<int,int> > s; // initialize DS
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if(s.empty()) {
                s.insert(make_pair(nums[i], 1)); // add first element with length = 1
            }
            else {
               multiset<pair<int,int> >::iterator it = s.lower_bound(make_pair(nums[i] - 1, 0));
                if(it == s.end() || it->first != nums[i] - 1) { // if no sequence exists with last element as current element - 1, 
                    s.insert(make_pair(nums[i], 1)); // create a new sequence with current element, length of sequence = 1
                }
                else {
                    int len = it->second; // find length of the sequence you want to insert it into
                    s.erase(it); // erase old sequence data
                    s.insert(make_pair(nums[i], len + 1)); // add the current element to this sequence & increase seq length by 1
                }
            }
        }
        for(multiset<pair<int,int> >::iterator it = s.begin(); it != s.end(); it++) {
            if(it->second < 3) return false; // if set has a sequence of length < 3, return false
        }
        return true; // possible

    }
};
```

